# Mermaid Diagram Standards

## Diagram Types for IT Strategy
- **Flowcharts**: For process flows, decision trees, and workflow documentation
- **Timeline/Gantt**: For project roadmaps and initiative timelines
- **Entity Relationship**: For system architecture and data relationships
- **Sequence Diagrams**: For system interactions and integration flows
- **Mind Maps**: For brainstorming and concept organization

## Formatting Standards
- Use clear, descriptive labels for all nodes and connections
- Maintain consistent styling within each diagram
- Keep diagrams readable by limiting complexity per diagram
- Use professional color schemes appropriate for business documents

## Business Context Integration
- Include business process names and terminology
- Show clear relationships between business drivers and IT initiatives
- Represent current state vs. future state architectures
- Highlight critical paths and dependencies

## Common IT Strategy Diagram Patterns
```mermaid
graph TB
    A[Business Objective] --> B[IT Capability Required]
    B --> C[Current State Gap]
    C --> D[Strategic Initiative]
    D --> E[Expected Outcome]
```

## Diagram Placement
- Place diagrams close to related text content
- Include descriptive captions explaining the diagram's purpose
- Reference diagrams in the text to guide reader understanding
- Consider diagram size for readability in final document format
